<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
				<jats:p>The recognition and the activation mechanism of the H<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> histamine receptor was studied based on quantum-chemical calculations. A mechanistic model proposed both for recognition and activation stage clarifies different properties of histamine and α-methylhistamine at the H<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> receptor. Interaction with a hypothetical receptor sites leads to the opening of the intramolecular hydrogen bonding in histamine, whereas the α-methylhistamine remains in closed conformation.</jats:p>
title: Studies on Activation of H3 Histamine Receptor: A Mechanistic Model

items.abstract: <jats:p>The determinants for recognition at H<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> histamine receptors are considered. Findings based on quantum-chemical calculations suggest that H<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> histamine receptor is less hydrophilic than the H<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>. The form most likely to be recognized by the H<jats:sub>3</jats:sub> receptor is an intramolecularly hydrogen-bonded form of α-methylhistamine. Receptor environment and hydration effects of active form of histamine analogs are of crucial importance</jats:p>
title: Theoretical Studies on Molecular Determinants for Recognition at H3 Histamine Receptors
